post.body:
Chinese are complex, mostly out of your life context. As a result learning Chinese with a traditional thinking is hard. And that is why extremely few foreign people are able to master Chinese. 

Here are some basic assumptions I think make sense before you try to learn Chinese:

- your purpose of learning Chinese should not be effective communication; even for Chinese, given they know some English, Chinese is not the most effective tool for communication; it is cumbersome, complex, obscure in many ways and situations;
- your purpose should be aesthetics, philosophy, intellectual curioisity, and mental experiment; when you think this way, Chinese becomes fun to examine and learn;
- your focus should be words; sentence, grammar, thought, let's pospone these to very very later stage of study
